{{Infobox person |name = Per Fugelli |image = Per Fugelli (square).jpg |image_size = |caption = Fugelli in 2008 |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date |1943|12|7|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Stavanger]], Norway |death_date = {{Death date and age |2017|9|13|1943|12|7|df=y}} |death_place = [[Jæren]], Norway |nationality = Norwegian |occupation = Physician, professor, author |awards = [[Fritt Ord Award]] }}
'''Per Fugelli''' (7 December 1943 – 13 September 2017) was a Norwegian physician and professor of [[General Practice]] at the [[University of Bergen]] from 1984 to 1992, and [[social medicine]] at the [[University of Oslo]] from 1992 until his death in 2017.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Per Fugelli |first= |last= |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |editor-last=Godal | editor-first=Anne Marit | editor-link=Anne Marit Godal |publisher=Norsk nettleksikon |location=Oslo |url=http://snl.no/Per_Fugelli|language=Norwegian|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Fugelli was born in [[Stavanger]], Norway, on December 7, 1943. He studied medicine at [[University of Oslo]].<ref name=lancet>Barbara Casassus. [https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(17)32737-X Obituary Per Fugelli.] The Lancet, Volume 390, No. 10107, p2032, 4 November 2017</ref>
==Career== From 1971–73 Fugelli was a general practitioner in [[Værøy]] and [[Røst]], and from 1977 to 1980 in [[Porsanger]]. During this time he earned his PhD and graduated in 1978. In 1984, he became a Professor of [[General Practice]] at the [[University of Bergen]], where he stayed until 1992. He became a Professor of [[social medicine]] at University of Oslo´s Institute of Health and Society. In 2013, he became Emeritus.<ref name=lancet/>
==Legacy== In 1993 Fugelli wrote: "The patient Earth is sick. Global environmental disruptions can have serious consequences for human health. It's time for doctors to give a world diagnosis and advise on treatment," <ref name=lancet/> predating the founding of [[planetary health]]. He is the subject of the documentary ''I die'' by filmmaker [[Erik Poppe]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nfi.no/eng/film?name=per-fugelli--i-die&id=1859|title=Per Fugelli - I die|last=|first=|date=|work=Norwegian Film Institute|access-date=2018-08-29|language=nb-NO}}</ref>
==Publications== He was a frequent contributor to the public debate on health and medical questions. Among his early books are ''Tilbake til huslegen'' from 1975, ''Doktor på Værøy og Røst'' from 1977, and ''Helsetilstand og helsetjeneste på Værøy og Røst'' from 1978.
He published the essay collections ''Med sordin og kanon'' and ''Helse og rettferdighet'' in 1990, ''0-visjonen'' in 2003, and ''Nokpunktet'' in 2008. He has been editor or co-editor of several works, including ''Huslegen'' from 1985, ''Medisinsk leksikon'' from 1990, ''Medisin og helse'' from 1993, and ''Verdier og penger i helsetjenesten'' from 2009.<ref name=uio-booklist>{{cite web|title=Liste over Per Fugellis bøker |url=http://folk.uio.no/pfugelli/ref_boker.htm |publisher=University of Oslo |language=Norwegian|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fugelli | first1 = P | year = 2006 | title = The Zero-vision: potential side effects of communicating health perfection and zero risk | url = | journal = Patient Educ Couns | volume = 60 | issue = 3| pages = 267–271 | doi = 10.1016/j.pec.2005.11.002 | pmid = 16469471 }}</ref>
==Personal life== Fugelli was married, had two children, and three grandchildren by the time he died.<ref name=lancet/>
In 2009, he was diagnosed with colorectal cancer. It metastasized into his lungs and by 2012, the cancer was declared terminal. Nevertheless, Fugelli continued to write and work as long as he was able, with his final published article written six weeks before his death. He died at [[Jæren]] on 13 September 2017, aged 73.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/per-fugelli/per-fugelli-er-doed/a/24115227/ |title= Per Fugelli er død |date =13 September 2017 |first1=Mona |last1=Langset |first2=Maiken |last2=Svendsen |newspaper =VG |accessdate=13 September 2017|language =no }}</ref>
==Awards== Fugelli won the 2010 Karl Evang Prize and in 2013, the Freedom of Expression Foundation Prize.<ref name=lancet/> {{s-start}} {{s-ach|aw}} {{s-bef | before= [[Sara Azmeh Rasmussen]] }} {{s-ttl | title = Recipient of the [[Fritt Ord Award]] | years = 2013 }} {{s-aft | after = [[Anne Sender]] }} {{s-end}}
