{{short description|A prehistoric continent that consisted of Australia, New Guinea, Tasmania and Seram}} '''Sahul''' was a prehistoric continent that consisted of [[Australia (continent)|Australia]], [[New Guinea]], [[Tasmania]] and [[Seram]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/sahul-pleistocene-continent-172704|title=What Did Australia Look Like When the First People Arrived?|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.pl/books?id=lQR1AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=prehistoric+continent+sahul&source=bl&ots=qwC2lfD2mP&sig=VNAwnQLMLOETIEh1rG_hyP-TZF0&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiRg6yj-d3cAhVvU98KHa4fCQsQ6AEwD3oECCgQAQ#v=onepage&q=prehistoric+continent+sahul&f=false|title=Anthropology and Global History: From Tribes to the Modern World-System|first=Robert M.|last=Carmack|date=11 October 2013|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.pl/books?id=JZRODwAAQBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=prehistoric+continent+sahul&source=bl&ots=POb582OzT1&sig=rzE7-bDfxRVKJXSnm0Qlxe5Qf9Y&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi2wZzM_N3cAhVpz1QKHZ7CDvUQ6AEwD3oECCgQAQ#v=onepage&q=prehistoric+continent+sahul&f=false|title=The Oxford Handbook of Prehistoric Oceania|first1=Terry L.|last1=Hunt|first2=Ethan E.|last2=Cochrane|date=8 August 2018|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.pl/books?id=KSkIKYztV_AC&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=seram+island+continent+sahul&source=bl&ots=ZhmqFgPcYj&sig=06I6ObyxajSRfq7OOLXgruDmrh0&hl=pl&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj_r6Lkh97cAhXMJt8KHVenBIwQ6AEwF3oECCgQAQ#v=onepage&q=seram+island+continent+sahul&f=false|title=The Archaeology of the Aru Islands, Eastern Indonesia|first1=Sue|last1=O'Connor|first2=Peter Marius|last2=Veth|first3=Matthew|last3=Spriggs|date=1 February 2007|publisher=ANU E Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>
Sahul was partially submerged around 18,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-04-island-hopping-route-people-australia.html|title=Island-hopping study shows the most likely route the first people took to Australia|publisher=}}</ref>
Sahul and Sunda were points of early human migrations after leaving Africa.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Biological Aspects of Human Migration|author1=Mascie-Taylor, D.B.A.C.G.N.|author2=Mascie-Taylor, C.G.N.|author3=Lasker, G.W.|date=1988|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521331098|url=https://books.google.pl/books?id=eJD5XJlviukC&pg=PA18|page=18|accessdate=2018-08-09}}</ref>
